      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The main scientific arguments and data regarding differences in average IQ scores between racial groups often cite studies that show, on average, white individuals score higher on IQ tests compared to Black and Hispanic individuals. Proponents argue that genetic factors play a significant role in these differences, pointing to heritability estimates and twin studies. They also reference historical and socio-economic factors that may contribute to disparities in educational opportunities and access to resources. Critics, however, argue that IQ tests are culturally biased and that environmental factors, such as poverty and discrimination, significantly impact test performance. Overall, the debate centers on the interplay between genetics and environment in shaping IQ scores across different racial groups.",
